{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472622"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.41,0.1,0.08,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77526"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1550"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"822"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48990"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77526"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA mother takes her 3-year-old daughter to her general practitioner as the child has persistent pain in her right arm. The pain started after she fell off a swing at the local playground yesterday. On examination there is no obvious deformity and the child has a full range of movement, although this is painful. There is some tenderness at the wrist. The doctor arranges an X-ray (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Below-elbow cast for two weeks","Below-elbow cast backslab with review in one week","Above-elbow cast for six weeks","Above-elbow backslab with review in one week","Reduction of fracture and wrist splint for three weeks"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor children presenting with a fracture it is important to determine the fracture type: is it a buckle injury or complete fracture? If it is a complete fracture, is it undisplaced or displaced, and how angulated is the distal fragment? These characteristics will help decide the management and follow-up of the fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the case, the X-ray shows a complete fracture that extends through both of cortices of the bone and with 15 degrees of angulation (Image). For fractures that are angulated, there is an acceptable range of angulation where clinicians feel comfortable plastering the arm and allowing it to heal without requiring a reduction. The degree of angulation is dependent on the age of the child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this instance, as per the Royal Children Hospital\u0027s (RCH) fracture guidelines, an angulation of \u0026lt;20 degrees is acceptable for children aged 0-5 years and as such, there is no need for any reduction in this child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenerally, for older children with complete and minimally displaced fractures, RCH guidelines recommend a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebelow-elbow\u003C/strong\u003E cast for six weeks. However, given the young age of this patient and the risk of movement, it is prudent to consider an\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eabove-elbow backslab to ensure minimal movement during the recovery process as after the pain subsides over the next few days, she is very likely start to move her wrist! Hospital protocols will vary and a below elbow full cast for five weeks would be quite appropriate. In this particular case, the advice from the expert at the Adelaide Women and Children\u0027s Hospital is a below elbow full cast for five weeks. The key issue would be the early review and assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll complete fractures must be reviewed in an outpatient fracture clinic within seven days and an X-ray of the cast being performed to ensure the appropriate positioning of the cast.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["There is an acceptable range of angulation for distal radial and ulnar fractures that do not require reduction.","All complete fractures must be reviewed in an outpatient fracture/orthopedic clinic within seven days."],"references":["Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Clinical Guidelines on Distal Radius and/or Ulna Fractures - https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/fractures/Distal_radius_and_or_ulna_metaphyseal_fractures_Emergency_Department_setting/#Reduction"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19588"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20939"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19588"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0d178e92-32c3-4df7-8280-1f45de898e32.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0d178e92-32c3-4df7-8280-1f45de898e32.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":774}},{"type":"media","id":"20939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20939"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iYQ1VgQFdA8ewzHQicv2puM82oZklK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iYQ1VgQFdA8ewzHQicv2puM82oZklK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":774}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic